<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,151,247]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,151,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zelazny &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2011" box="[330,513,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Alara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornigera">
<emphasis box="[330,513,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Alara cornigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Zelazny" authorityName="Zelazny" authorityYear="1981" box="[644,850,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Alara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cervus">
<emphasis box="[644,750,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">A. cervus</emphasis>
Zelazny
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<collectingCountry box="[966,1092,151,175]" name="Philippines" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Philippines</collectingCountry>
in structure and coloration. It can be distinguished by its larger size, by the separated dorsal processes of the genital styles, and by the aedeagus having smaller dorsal processes on the stem and a more curved apical portion.
</paragraph>
